title: For Sale/Trade:   Rare 1917 REMINGTON ARMORY WW1 USA-MADE Mosin-Nagant 7.62
postcontent: This rifle is a PRISTINE example of a rare make of 7.62 Russian Mosin that was produced for 2 years only (1916-1917) by the REMINGTON ARMORY in the United States to aid the Russian Army at the end of WW I . They were held back from release from the armory in early 1917 at the outbreak of the Russian Revolution. This gun has been in the possession of a local collector in Spokane for many years and is like it just came off the line!  ALL the numbered components match on this rifle and the bore is excellent. This rifle functions flawlessly -like it is brand new! All of the proper USA trade stamps are on the steel and Russian exchange markings as well. The market value of this gun (my research shows) is $1,200 - and up .  The only modification done to this gun is that the stock has been slightly Sporterized for practical use and easier handling.  Thus , the reduction in price to $695.00...Own a cool piece of American World War 1 history with this rare 1917 Rifle! E-mail , if interested for more detailed pics.

title: For Sale:  War of 1812 Battle of the Miami, Fort Meigs, Ohio
postcontent:
For offer is a 200-year old copy of the New York Evening Post, dated Tuesday, February 16th, 1813. It contains fragmentary yet sensationalistic snippets from the Battle of the Miami which had occurred the previous May, as well as a brief account of the British blockage of Chesapeake Bay which had begun that month. It also contains a lengthy excerpt from an anti-war speech by Congressman James Elliott arguing that the Madison administration had not made strong enough efforts to negotiate a peace with Great Britain. A very interesting piece consisting of a single sheet folded into two leaves, for pages total. Mostly advertisements, with snippets of news shoehorned in. 

Shipping $12.35 priority mail.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Enfield 38 S&W Revolver
postcontent:
Chambered for .38-200 (not a 38 special), a cartridge specifically designed for military use, the Enfield No. 2 Mk 1 was the standard British sidearm in the Second World War. The No. 2 Mk 1 was born when British authorities began searching for a double-action revolver with less weight and recoil than the Webley they'd been using, that could be quickly mastered by a minimally-trained soldier and gave him a good probability of hitting an enemy with the first shot at extremely close ranges. The .38-200 round was created by combining a .38 S&W catridge with a 200 grain bullet. By using such a long, heavy, round-nosed lead bullet in a .38 caliber cartridge, it was found that the bullet, being minimally stabilized for its weight and caliber, tended to tumble longitudinally when striking an object, theoretically increasing wounding and stopping ability of human targets at short ranges. This double-action-only revolver features a fixed blade front sight with a rear groove, and a saddle ring. Its metal is in fair condition and its bore is in good condition.

Includes: 2 boxes of 38S&W (50 each) and a very nice basket weave leather holster.
$295.  This is an awesome deal on this pistol plus you get ammo and a holster!

Would consider partial trade for 22LR ammo (no junk)

Similar pistols like this have been listed for sale on GM & Cabela's for $500-$600 (have copies of ads) for just the pistol.

If you ever watched Lawrence of Arabia, he carried a gun similar to this.  He was a British Officer.  No collection is complete without an Enfield.  Or shoot for fun.

Cash-F to F. Must have proof of ID (DL) Must be legally able to purchase and sign a Bill of Sale

title: For Sale:  Rare Colt Model 1905 Marine Corps
postcontent:
This Colt Model 1905 Marine Corps is a .38 revolver issued by the United States Marine Corps during the period from 1905 to 1909. It is a variation of the Colt M1892 with a rounded grip frame. A small number (less than 850) are known to have been issued under military contract. These revolvers are marked on the butt with the appropriate USMC markings and are serial numbered 001 through at least 812. A further 926 copies were made between 1905 and 1909 for the commercial (civilian) market, and these revolvers are serial numbered on the butt from 10001 through 10926.


This weapon is in fair condition and is fully functional. 

Trading Post Knife and Pawn

title: For Sale/Trade:  ART 3-9x40
postcontent:
NEW in the box ART 3-9x40 Here is a chance to buy a VERY RARE, fully functional sniper Rifle Scope. This scope was designed by Jim Leatherwood, the famous designer/creator of the ART I and ART II sniper scopes used in Southeast Asia to enable a sniper with only moderate training to accurately shoot out to 800 meters without running through all the calculations and compensations to manually adjust for the ballsitics of the load being fired. Jim Leatherwood created the ART / MPC after the ART II, taking the knowledge learned with the military applications of his Auto-Ranging-Sniper scopes, and applying them in the design and productions of an Auto-Ranging scope for non-warfare use.
This particular ART / MPC has a low serial number (008775) and is complete with the mounting/ranging "saddle" that fits on Weaver and similar one-piece bases. This scope was manufactured under contract by Weaver Scope Company.
The ART / MPC is calibrated to automatically compensate for load trajectories over ranges from 200 to 600 meters. Unlike the ART I and ART II, which were calibrated for a single caliber and load, the manual for the ART / MPC contains settings for over 100 calibers / loads, ranging from the .17 Remington to the .375 H&H Magnum. 

Condition is new old stock! It comes with an inspection receipt, original box and copy of ART MPC manual VAL AT $1,200.00
